{"title_page": "Eddie Zuko", "text_new": "{{short description|American singer and songwriter}}\n{{multiple issues |1=\n{{notability|date=January 2020}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Eddie Monks\n| image              =\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Heriberto Xavier Culebro\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1993|11|16}}\n| birth_place        = [[Brawley, California]]\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Singer, songwriter\n| years_active       = 2017 \u2013 present\n}}\n\n'''Heriberto Xavier Culebro''' (born November 16, 1993),{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} known professionally as '''Eddie Zuko''', is a [[Chicano]] singer and songwriter from [[Imperial, California]].\n\n== Life  ==\nZuko was born to Mexican-American parents Heriberto Culebro and Aida Culebro Aguirre in [[Brawley, California]] in [[Imperial Valley]],{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} which is home to many Latinos, specifically Mexican-Americans. Zuko began singing and recording music at the age of 11 with his family. As a young boy, his father introduced him to hip hop culture via the movie ''[[Beat Street]]'', which sparked his interest in hip hop music.<ref name=\"CandidChronicle\">{{Cite web|url=https://candidchronicle.com/westcoastwednesdays-presents-eddie-zuko/|title=#WestCoastWednesdays presents Eddie Zuko|last=Cara Anderson|date=2018-04-11|website=Candid Chronicle|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> At the age of 16, Zuko began performing in the surrounding areas of Imperial County, such as [[quincea\u00f1era]]s, [[Lowrider|lowrider shows]], and birthday parties, and high school football game halftime shows, which helped him launch his music career.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lataco.com/tune-of-the-day-eddie-zuko-made-an-ode-to-growing-up-brown-in-socal/|title=Tune of the Day ~ Eddie Zuko, \u2018Made,\u2019 an Ode to Growing Up Brown in SoCal|last=Hern|first=Daniel|last2=ez|date=2018-07-30|website=L.A. TACO|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> Zuko moved to San Diego where he resided until late 2017, when he moved to Los Angeles.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n== Career ==\nIn May 2017, Zuko released his EP titled ''El Zuko'', which consists of five songs in both English and Spanish, featuring [[Hip hop music|rap music]] and elements of elements of [[reggae]], [[Rock music|rock]], and [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]].{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} The EP was produced by Anomeric, with the exception of \"Made\" which was produced by Zuko himself.<ref name=\"CandidChronicle\" /> On the EP, the song \"Made\" discusses his childhood growing up in Imperial Valley, in addition to his life experiences that tell of his heritage and the influences that made him into the person he is today.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nA frequent collaborator of Eddie Zuko is Paul Redona, a music producer who collaborated with Zuko on the song \"Tamales\". In addition, Eddie Zuko featured as a guest vocalist on the song \"One Day at a Time\" on [[Sublime with Rome]]'s third album ''[[Blessings (Sublime with Rome album)|Blessings]]''.\n\n== Discography ==\n'''EPs'''\n*''El Zuko'' (2017)\n\n'''Singles'''\n*\"Enemy\" (2017)\n*\"Tamales (Reprise)\" (2019)\n*\"Mijo\" (2019)\n\n'''Collaborations with other artists''' \n*\"One Day at a Time\" (with [[Sublime with Rome]]) (2019)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=462&v=QK5Zi5LDxlg Eddie Zuko's Performance at a High School Football Game] \n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=1928&v=U1YU4aZ98E8 Eddie Zuko Interview] \n*[https://twitter.com/spagheddiexavi Artist's Twitter]\n*[https://soundcloud.com/eddiezuko Artist's SoundCloud]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zuko, Eddie}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:American people of Mexican descent|*]]\n[[Category:Chicano| ]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American singer and songwriter}}\n{{multiple issues |1=\n{{notability|date=January 2020}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Eddie Zuko\n| image              =\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Heriberto Xavier Culebro\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1993|11|16}}\n| birth_place        = [[Brawley, California]]\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Singer, songwriter\n| years_active       = 2017 \u2013 present\n}}\n\n'''Heriberto Xavier Culebro''' (born November 16, 1993),{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} known professionally as '''Eddie Zuko''', is a [[Chicano]] singer and songwriter from [[Imperial, California]].\n\n== Life  ==\nZuko was born to Mexican-American parents Heriberto Culebro and Aida Culebro Aguirre in [[Brawley, California]] in [[Imperial Valley]],{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} which is home to many Latinos, specifically Mexican-Americans. Zuko began singing and recording music at the age of 11 with his family. As a young boy, his father introduced him to hip hop culture via the movie ''[[Beat Street]]'', which sparked his interest in hip hop music.<ref name=\"CandidChronicle\">{{Cite web|url=https://candidchronicle.com/westcoastwednesdays-presents-eddie-zuko/|title=#WestCoastWednesdays presents Eddie Zuko|last=Cara Anderson|date=2018-04-11|website=Candid Chronicle|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> At the age of 16, Zuko began performing in the surrounding areas of Imperial County, such as [[quincea\u00f1era]]s, [[Lowrider|lowrider shows]], and birthday parties, and high school football game halftime shows, which helped him launch his music career.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lataco.com/tune-of-the-day-eddie-zuko-made-an-ode-to-growing-up-brown-in-socal/|title=Tune of the Day ~ Eddie Zuko, \u2018Made,\u2019 an Ode to Growing Up Brown in SoCal|last=Hern|first=Daniel|last2=ez|date=2018-07-30|website=L.A. TACO|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> Zuko moved to San Diego where he resided until late 2017, when he moved to Los Angeles.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n== Career ==\nIn May 2017, Zuko released his EP titled ''El Zuko'', which consists of five songs in both English and Spanish, featuring [[Hip hop music|rap music]] and elements of elements of [[reggae]], [[Rock music|rock]], and [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]].{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} The EP was produced by Anomeric, with the exception of \"Made\" which was produced by Zuko himself.<ref name=\"CandidChronicle\" /> On the EP, the song \"Made\" discusses his childhood growing up in Imperial Valley, in addition to his life experiences that tell of his heritage and the influences that made him into the person he is today.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nA frequent collaborator of Eddie Zuko is Paul Redona, a music producer who collaborated with Zuko on the song \"Tamales\". In addition, Eddie Zuko featured as a guest vocalist on the song \"One Day at a Time\" on [[Sublime with Rome]]'s third album ''[[Blessings (Sublime with Rome album)|Blessings]]''.\n\n== Discography ==\n'''EPs'''\n*''El Zuko'' (2017)\n\n'''Singles'''\n*\"Enemy\" (2017)\n*\"Tamales (Reprise)\" (2019)\n*\"Mijo\" (2019)\n\n'''Collaborations with other artists''' \n*\"One Day at a Time\" (with [[Sublime with Rome]]) (2019)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=462&v=QK5Zi5LDxlg Eddie Zuko's Performance at a High School Football Game] \n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=1928&v=U1YU4aZ98E8 Eddie Zuko Interview] \n*[https://twitter.com/spagheddiexavi Artist's Twitter]\n*[https://soundcloud.com/eddiezuko Artist's SoundCloud]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zuko, Eddie}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:American people of Mexican descent|*]]\n[[Category:Chicano| ]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "2605:e000:1e07:e109:c0b9:4fd7:cca8:651", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eddie_Zuko"}
{"title_page": "Leo Determan", "text_new": "{{short description|Sailor from the Netherlands}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sailor\n  | name           = Leo Determan\n  | image          = Leo Determan.png\n  | image_size     = \n  | caption        = Leo Determan in 2017 as spectator during the Soling Worlds at [[Muiden]], The Netherlands\n  | birth_name     =\n  | fullname       = \n  | nickname       = Deet\n  | nationality    = {{NED}}\n  | birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1949|4|7}}\n  | birth_place    = [[Rotterdam]]\n  | death_date     =\n  | death_place    =\n  | height         = {{convert|1.92|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n  | weight         =\n  | retired        =\n  | classes        = [[Flying Dutchman (dinghy)|Flying Dutchman]]<br />[[Tempest (keelboat)|Tempest]]<br />[[Soling]]\n  | club           = [[:nl:Vriendschap Zij Ons Doel|VZOD]], Rotterdam\n  | collegeteam    =\n  | coach          =\n  | medaltemplates-title =\n  | medaltemplates = \n    {{Medal|Country|{{NED}}}}\n      {{MedalCompetition|[[Vintage Yachting Games]]}}\n        {{Medal|Gold|2008 [[Medemblik]], [[Netherlands|The Netherlands]]|[[2008 Vintage Yachting Games \u2013 Soling|Soling]]}}\n  | show-medals    = yes\n  | updated        = 8 April 2020\n}}\n\n'''Leo Determan''' (born 7 April 1949 in [[Rotterdam]]) is a [[sailor]] from the [[Netherlands]], who represented his country at the [[2008 Vintage Yachting Games]] in [[Medemblik]] [[Netherlands|The Netherlands]]. Determan in the middle together with [[helmsman]] [[Rudy den Outer]] and [[Ronald den Arend]] on the foredeck took the [[Gold medal]] in the [[Soling]]. <ref name=\"Vintage\" /> \nLeo holds several [[Soling National Champions|Dutch titles]] (1995, 1999, 2000, 2008 and 2001) and one [[Soling National Champions|Italian title]] (2010) in the Soling. He used to be member of Yacht Club ''VZOD'', Rotterdam.\n[[File:VYG 1 Soling 2008.JPG|thumb|left|Leo Determan (middle) with Rudy den Outer and Ronald den Arend winning the [[2008 Vintage Yachting Games]] in [[Medemblik]].]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==Sailing==\nAfter sailing as crew on a \"[[:nl:Vrijheidklasse|Vrijheid class]]\", Determan purchased the [[Flying Dutchman (dinghy)|Flying Dutchman]] H 125 \"Aquarius\" in 1970. With Rudy den Outer he sailed Flying Dutchman, [[:nl:Spanker|Spanker]] (a Dutch National class) and Soling for many years and for a brief period [[Tempest (keelboat)|Tempest]]. Depending on the class they changed positions as crew or helmsman.\n[[File:FD H125.jpg|left|thumb|Leo Determan (right) and Rudy den Outer in the Flying Dutchman ''Aquarius'' on the Kralingsche Plas, Netherlands in 1970]]\n{{clear}}\n\n== Professional life ==\nDeterman works in the [[mineral oil]] industry. In 2005 [[:nl:Gulf Oil|Gulf Oil Nederland]] BV in [[Den Helder]] named her new [[Tanker (ship)|Bunker barge]] after Determan. <ref name=\"Tanker\" /><ref name=\"Tanker2\" />\n[[File:De Leo Determan (Tanker).jpg|left|thumb|Dutch Tankership \"Leo Determan\"]]\n{{clear}}\n{{Footer Italian Championship Winners in Soling}}\n{{Footer Dutch Championship Winners in Soling}}\n\n{{Netherlands-yachtracing-bio-stub}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs =\n <ref name=Tanker>{{cite web\n   |url        = https://www.debinnenvaart.nl/schip_detail/7154/\n   |title      = LEO DETERMAN\n   |publisher  = Vereniging \"De Binnenvaart\"\n   |accessdate = 8 April 2020\n  }}</ref>\n <ref name=Tanker2>{{cite web\n   |url        = https://www.marinetraffic.com/nl/ais/details/ships/shipid:242854/mmsi:244700188/imo:0/vessel:LEO_DETERMAN\n   |title      = LEO DETERMAN\n   |publisher  = Marine Traffic\n   |accessdate = 8 April 2020\n  }}</ref>\n <ref name=Vintage>{{cite web\n   |url=http://www.soling.com/results/ShowResults.asp?ID=459\n   |title=Vintage Yachting Games 2008\n   |year=2008\n   |website=www.soling.com\n   |publisher=International Soling Association|location=Buenos Aires (ARG)\n   |access-date=8 April 2015\n }}</ref>\n}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Determan, Leo}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Rotterdam]]\n[[Category:Dutch male sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:Flying Dutchman class sailors]]\n[[Category:Soling class sailors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Sailor from the Netherlands}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sailor\n  | name           = Leo Determan\n  | image          = Leo Determan.png\n  | image_size     = \n  | caption        = Leo Determan in 2017 as spectator during the Soling Worlds at [[Muiden]], The Netherlands\n  | birth_name     =\n  | fullname       = \n  | nickname       = Deet\n  | nationality    = {{NED}}\n  | birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1949|4|7}}\n  | birth_place    = [[Rotterdam]]\n  | death_date     =\n  | death_place    =\n  | height         = {{convert|1.92|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n  | weight         =\n  | retired        =\n  | classes        = [[Flying Dutchman (dinghy)|Flying Dutchman]]<br />[[Tempest (keelboat)|Tempest]]<br />[[Soling]]\n  | club           = [[:nl:Vriendschap Zij Ons Doel|VZOD]], Rotterdam\n  | collegeteam    =\n  | coach          =\n  | medaltemplates-title =\n  | medaltemplates = \n    {{Medal|Country|{{NED}}}}\n      {{MedalCompetition|[[Vintage Yachting Games]]}}\n        {{Medal|Gold|2008 [[Medemblik]], [[Netherlands|The Netherlands]]|[[2008 Vintage Yachting Games \u2013 Soling|Soling]]}}\n  | show-medals    = yes\n  | updated        = 8 April 2020\n}}\n\n'''Leo Determan''' (born 7 April 1949 in [[Rotterdam]]) is a [[sailor]] from the [[Netherlands]], who represented his country at the [[2008 Vintage Yachting Games]] in [[Medemblik]] [[Netherlands|The Netherlands]]. Determan in the middle together with [[helmsman]] [[Rudy den Outer]] and [[Ronald den Arend]] on the foredeck took the [[Gold medal]] in the [[Soling]]. <ref name=\"Vintage\" /> \nLeo holds several [[Soling National Champions|Dutch titles]] (1995, 1999, 2000, 2008 and 2001) and one [[Soling National Champions|Italian title]] (2010) in the Soling. He used to be member of Yacht Club ''VZOD'', Rotterdam.\n[[File:VYG 1 Soling 2008.JPG|thumb|left|Leo Determan (middle) with Rudy den Outer and Ronald den Arend winning the [[2008 Vintage Yachting Games]] in [[Medemblik]].]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==Sailing==\nAfter sailing as crew on a \"[[:nl:Vrijheidklasse|Vrijheid class]]\", Determan purchased the [[Flying Dutchman (dinghy)|Flying Dutchman]] H 125 \"Aquarius\" in 1970. With Rudy den Outer he sailed Flying Dutchman, [[:nl:Spanker|Spanker]] (a Dutch National class) and Soling for many years and for a brief period [[Tempest (keelboat)|Tempest]]. Depending on the class they changed positions as crew or helmsman.\n[[File:FD H125.jpg|left|thumb|Leo Determan (right) and Rudy den Outer in the Flying Dutchman ''Aquarius'' on the Kralingsche Plas, Netherlands in 1970]]\n{{clear}}\n\n== Professional life ==\nDeterman works in the [[mineral oil]] industry. In 2005 [[:nl:Gulf Oil|Gulf Oil Nederland]] BV in [[Den Helder]] named her new [[Tanker (ship)|Bunker barge]] after Determan. <ref name=\"Tanker\" /><ref name=\"Tanker2\" />\n[[File:De Leo Determan (Tanker).jpg|left|thumb|Dutch Tankership \"Leo Determan\"]]\n{{clear}}\n{{Footer Italian Championship Winners in Soling}}\n{{Footer Dutch Champions in Soling}}\n\n{{Netherlands-yachtracing-bio-stub}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs =\n <ref name=Tanker>{{cite web\n   |url        = https://www.debinnenvaart.nl/schip_detail/7154/\n   |title      = LEO DETERMAN\n   |publisher  = Vereniging \"De Binnenvaart\"\n   |accessdate = 8 April 2020\n  }}</ref>\n <ref name=Tanker2>{{cite web\n   |url        = https://www.marinetraffic.com/nl/ais/details/ships/shipid:242854/mmsi:244700188/imo:0/vessel:LEO_DETERMAN\n   |title      = LEO DETERMAN\n   |publisher  = Marine Traffic\n   |accessdate = 8 April 2020\n  }}</ref>\n <ref name=Vintage>{{cite web\n   |url=http://www.soling.com/results/ShowResults.asp?ID=459\n   |title=Vintage Yachting Games 2008\n   |year=2008\n   |website=www.soling.com\n   |publisher=International Soling Association|location=Buenos Aires (ARG)\n   |access-date=8 April 2015\n }}</ref>\n}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Determan, Leo}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Rotterdam]]\n[[Category:Dutch male sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:Flying Dutchman class sailors]]\n[[Category:Soling class sailors]]\n", "name_user": "Dragon Genoa", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leo_Determan"}
{"title_page": "Beth Littleford", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| image       = BethLittlefordApr2011.jpg\n| caption     = Littleford at the Night of Comedy 9 benefit to support the [[Children Affected by AIDS Foundation]] (CAAF) in [[Beverly Hills, California]].\n| name        = Beth Littleford\n| birth_name  = Elizabeth Anna Halcyon Littleford\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1968|7|17}}\n| birth_place  = [[Nashville, Tennessee]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| occupation  = Actress, comedian, television personality\n| residence = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| years_active = 1996\u2013present\n| spouse      = Rob Fox (1998\u20132015; divorced)\n| children = 2\n}}\n\n'''Elizabeth Anna Halcyon Littleford'''<ref name=\"filmr\"/> (born July 17, 1968) is an American [[actress]], [[comedian]], and [[television personality]]. She was one of the original correspondents on ''[[The Daily Show]]'' on [[Comedy Central]] from 1996 to 2000. Littleford has also appeared in the shows ''[[I'm in the Band]]'' and ''[[Dog with a Blog]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nLittleford was born in [[Nashville, Tennessee]], the daughter of Jackie, a professor, and Philip O. Littleford, a cardiologist and inventor. She grew up in [[Winter Park, Florida]].<ref name=\"filmr\">[http://www.filmreference.com/film/23/Beth-Littleford.html Beth Littleford Biography (1968-)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> She lives in [[Los Angeles, California]] with one son, Jackson Oliver Fox (born on July 30, 2005) and an adopted daughter, Halcyon \u2018Hallie\u2019 Juna (born on March 23, 2012).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://celebritybabies.people.com/2012/03/24/beth-littleford-welcomes-daughter-halcyon-juna/| title=Beth Littleford Welcomes Daughter Halcyon Juna| publisher=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=March 24, 2012| accessdate= March 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=December 2017}}\nLittleford is perhaps most famous for her pioneering role as the first female correspondent on ''[[The Daily Show]]''. She has also guest-starred on numerous television programs beginning in the late 1990s such as ''[[Spin City]]'', ''[[The West Wing (TV series)|The West Wing]]'', ''[[Family Guy]]'', and ''[[Frasier]]''. Littleford was also a celebrity commentator on [[VH1]]'s ''[[I Love the 80s Strikes Back]]'' in 2003, ''[[I Love the '90s (U.S. TV series)|I Love the 90s]]'' in 2004, ''[[I Love the 90s: Part Deux]]'' in 2005, ''[[I Love the New Millennium]]'' and ''The Great Debate'' in 2009.\n\nShe was the female lead on the short-lived [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] series ''[[Method and Red]]'', and also starred as [[Ben Tennyson]]'s mother Sandra in ''[[Ben 10: Race Against Time]]'', and reprised the role in the ''[[Ben 10: Alien Force]]'' episode 20 and again in ''[[Ben 10: Ultimate Alien]]''.  She has appeared in TV commercials for [[The Laughing Cow|Laughing Cow]] cheese, Cascade, and a{{which|date=December 2017}} hotel chain.\n\nLittleford starred in the [[Disney XD]] original show ''[[I'm in the Band]]'', the 2010 Disney channel movie ''[[Starstruck (2010 film)|Starstruck]]'', and played Suzanne Berger on [[MTV]]'s ''[[The Hard Times of RJ Berger]],'' Dana on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[Desperate Housewives]],'' and the realtor on [[The Fosters (2013 TV series)|''The Fosters'']]. More recently, she had a starring role as Ellen Jennings in the [[Disney Channel]] original series ''[[Dog with a Blog]]'' and a guest appearance on ''[[Dead to Me (TV series)|Dead to Me]]'' on [[Netflix]].\n\nIn 2015, Littleford was given a [[Peabody Award]] for her groundbreaking work on ''[[The Daily Show]] with [[Jon Stewart]]'' from 1996-2000 as the show's \"Original Female Correspondent.\"\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1998\n|''{{sortname|A|Cool, Dry Place}}''\n|Suzanne\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''{{sortname|The|24 Hour Woman}}''\n|Lynn Shapiro\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Mystery, Alaska]]''\n|Janice Pettiboe\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''Picture This''\n|Patty\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Drillbit Taylor]]''\n|Barbara Drennan\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''Veiled''\n|Marie\n|Short\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Crazy, Stupid, Love]]''\n|Claire\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''Music High''\n|Lucy Bates\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''Kidnap Party''\n|Alison Slater\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|''It's Not You, It's Me''\n|Sandy\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''Random Tropical Paradise''\n|Martha Crandall\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''Senior Moment''\n|Tess Woodson\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[I'll Be Next Door for Christmas]]''\n| Fran\n| Christmas comedy film written and directed by David Jay Willis\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1996\u20132000\n|''[[The Daily Show]]''\n|Herself\n|Original Female Correspondent\n|-\n|1998\u20132000\n|''[[Spin City]]''\n|Deirdre West\n|Recurring role\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Boston Public]]''\n|Marcia Fennel\n|\"Chapter 24\"\n|-\n|2002\n|''{{sortname|The|West Wing}}''\n|WKZN Philadelphia Anchor Leslie\n|\"The U.S. Poet Laureate\"\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Still Standing (TV series)|Still Standing]]''\n|Kristy Duncan\n|\"Still in School\"\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[What I Like About You (TV series)|What I Like About You]]''\n|Susan\n|\"Copy That\"\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Andy Richter Controls the Universe]]''\n|Reggie Meadows\n|\"The Show Might Go On\"\n|-\n|2002\u201303\n|''[[Greetings from Tucson]]''\n|Marna\n|\"Popularity\", \"Student Council\"\n|-\n|2002\u201303\n|''[[Life with Bonnie]]''\n|Dr. 'Mrs.' Casey\n|\"Pilot\", \"No Matter Where You Go, There You Are\"\n|-\n|2003\n|''{{sortname|The|Big Wide World of Carl Laemke|nolink=1}}''\n|Laurie Laemke\n|TV film\n|-\n|2003\u201304\n|''[[One on One (TV series)|One on One]]''\n|Geraldine Murphy\n|Recurring role\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Method & Red]]''\n|Nancy Blaford\n|Main role\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Joey (TV series)|Joey]]''\n|Carla\n|\"Joey and the Premiere\"\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Rodney (TV series)|Rodney]]''\n|Amy O'Brien\n|\"Rodney Gets a Leg Up\"\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Love, Inc. (TV series)|Love, Inc.]]''\n|Charlene\n|\"Anything But Love\"\n|-\n|2006\u201312\n|''[[Family Guy]]''\n|Various (voice)\n|Guest role\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Without a Trace]]''\n|Diane Neese\n|\"Two of Us\"\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Ben 10: Race Against Time]]''\n|[[List of Ben 10 characters#Carl .26 Sandra Tennyson|Sandra Tennyson]]\n|TV film\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Samantha Who?]]''\n|Audrey Rhodes\n|\"The Girlfriend\"\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Ben 10: Alien Force]]''\n|Sandra Tennyson (voice)\n|\"Grounded\"\n|-\n|2009\n|''Take 2''\n|Amy\n|TV film\n|-\n|2009\u201310\n|''[[Rules of Engagement (TV series)|Rules of Engagement]]''\n|Laura\n|\"Twice\", \"Harassment\", \"Handy Man\"\n|-\n|2009\u201311\n|''[[I'm in the Band]]''\n|Beth Campbell\n|Regular role\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Starstruck (2010 film)|StarStruck]]''\n|Barbara Olson\n|TV film\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation]]''\n|Nurse Mona\n|\"Field Mice\"\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Ben 10: Ultimate Alien]]''\n|Sandra Tennyson (voice)\n|\"Hit 'Em Where They Live\"\n|-\n|2010\n|''{{sortname|The|New Adventures of Old Christine}}''\n|Tony Kershaw\n|\"Get Smarter\"\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Neighbors from Hell]]''\n|Various (voice)\n|Recurring role\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[CSI: Miami]]''\n|Elena Manus\n|\"Sleepless in Miami\"\n|-\n|2010\u201311\n|''{{sortname|The|Hard Times of RJ Berger}}''\n|Suzanne Berger\n|Recurring role\n|-\n|2010\u201313\n|''{{sortname|The|Cleveland Show}}''\n|Various (voice)\n|Guest role\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Desperate Housewives]]''\n|Dana\n|\"Then I Got Really Scared\", \"School of Hard Knocks\"\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Melissa & Joey]]''\n|Suzanne Haber\n|\"Good to Go\"\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Mad (TV series)|Mad]]''\n|Tasha / Various (voice)\n|1 episode\n|-\n|2012\u201315\n|''[[Dog with a Blog]]''\n|Ellen Jennings\n|Main role\n|-\n|2013\n|''{{sortname|The|Mindy Project}}''\n|Helen\n|\"Mindy's Minute\"\n|-\n|2013\u201314\n|''[[Ben 10: Omniverse]]''\n|Sandra Tennyson (voice)\n|\"Rules of Engagement\", \"O Mother, Where Art Thou?\", \"Vreedlemania\"\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Mistresses (U.S. TV series)|Mistresses]]''\n|Lindsay Lehman\n|\"Under Pressure\"\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Unwanted Guest]]''\n|Anna Roberts\n|TV film\n|-\n|2016\u201317\n|''{{sortname|The|Fosters|The Fosters (2013 TV series)}}''\n|Realtor\n|\"Girl Code\", \"New York\", \"Dream a Little Dream\"\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[2 Broke Girls]]''\n|Bonnie\n|\"And the Stalking Dead\"\n|-\n|2017\n|''Liberty Crossing''\n|Special Agent Margaret Smith\n|\"Comfort Zones\"\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[My Dead Ex]]''\n|Laurel \n|Recurring\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Dead to Me (TV series)|Dead to Me]]\n|Doug's Wife\n|\"I Can Handle It\"\n|-\n|2019\n|''Home Is Where the Killer Is''\n|Patricia Wade\n|TV Film\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website}}\n*{{IMDb name|514719|Beth Littleford}}\n\n{{The Daily Show}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Littleford, Beth}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:American women comedians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Nashville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Swarthmore College alumni]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:20th-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| image       = BethLittlefordApr2011.jpg\n| caption     = Littleford at the Night of Comedy 9 benefit to support the [[Children Affected by AIDS Foundation]] (CAAF) in [[Beverly Hills, California]].\n| name        = Beth Littleford\n| birth_name  = Elizabeth Anna Halcyon Littleford\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1968|7|17}}\n| birth_place  = [[Nashville, Tennessee]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| occupation  = Actress, comedian, television personality\n| residence = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| years_active = 1996\u2013present\n| spouse      = Rob Fox (1998\u20132015; divorced)\n| children = 2\n}}\n\n'''Elizabeth Anna Halcyon Littleford'''<ref name=\"filmr\"/> (born July 17, 1968) is an American [[actress]], [[comedian]], and [[television personality]]. She was one of the original correspondents on ''[[The Daily Show]]'' on [[Comedy Central]] from 1996 to 2000. Littleford has also appeared in the shows ''[[I'm in the Band]]'' and ''[[Dog with a Blog]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nLittleford was born in [[Nashville, Tennessee]], the daughter of Jackie, a professor, and Philip O. Littleford, a cardiologist and inventor. She grew up in [[Winter Park, Florida]].<ref name=\"filmr\">[http://www.filmreference.com/film/23/Beth-Littleford.html Beth Littleford Biography (1968-)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> She lives in [[Los Angeles, California]] with one son, Jackson Oliver Fox (born on July 30, 2005) and an adopted daughter, Halcyon \u2018Hallie\u2019 Juna (born on March 23, 2012).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://celebritybabies.people.com/2012/03/24/beth-littleford-welcomes-daughter-halcyon-juna/| title=Beth Littleford Welcomes Daughter Halcyon Juna| publisher=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=March 24, 2012| accessdate= March 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=December 2017}}\nLittleford is perhaps most famous for her pioneering role as the first female correspondent on ''[[The Daily Show]]''. She has also guest-starred on numerous television programs beginning in the late 1990s such as ''[[Spin City]]'', ''[[The West Wing (TV series)|The West Wing]]'', ''[[Family Guy]]'', and ''[[Frasier]]''. Littleford was also a celebrity commentator on [[VH1]]'s ''[[I Love the 80s Strikes Back]]'' in 2003, ''[[I Love the '90s (U.S. TV series)|I Love the 90s]]'' in 2004, ''[[I Love the 90s: Part Deux]]'' in 2005, ''[[I Love the New Millennium]]'' and ''The Great Debate'' in 2009.\n\nShe was the female lead on the short-lived [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] series ''[[Method and Red]]'', and also starred as [[Ben Tennyson]]'s mother Sandra in ''[[Ben 10: Race Against Time]]'', and reprised the role in the ''[[Ben 10: Alien Force]]'' episode 20 and again in ''[[Ben 10: Ultimate Alien]]''.  She has appeared in TV commercials for [[The Laughing Cow|Laughing Cow]] cheese, Cascade, and a{{which|date=December 2017}} hotel chain.\n\nLittleford starred in the [[Disney XD]] original show ''[[I'm in the Band]]'', the 2010 Disney channel movie ''[[Starstruck (2010 film)|Starstruck]]'', and played Suzanne Berger on [[MTV]]'s ''[[The Hard Times of RJ Berger]],'' Dana on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[Desperate Housewives]],'' and the realtor on [[The Fosters (2013 TV series)|''The Fosters'']]. More recently, she had a starring role as Ellen Jennings in the [[Disney Channel]] original series ''[[Dog with a Blog]]'' and a guest appearance on ''[[Dead to Me (TV series)|Dead to Me]]'' on [[Netflix]].\n\nIn 2015, Littleford was given a [[Peabody Award]] for her groundbreaking work on ''[[The Daily Show]] with [[Jon Stewart]]'' from 1996-2000 as the show's \"Original Female Correspondent.\"\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1998\n|''{{sortname|A|Cool, Dry Place}}''\n|Suzanne\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''{{sortname|The|24 Hour Woman}}''\n|Lynn Shapiro\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Mystery, Alaska]]''\n|Janice Pettiboe\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''Picture This''\n|Patty\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Drillbit Taylor]]''\n|Barbara Drennan\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''Veiled''\n|Marie\n|Short\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Crazy, Stupid, Love]]''\n|Claire\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''Music High''\n|Lucy Bates\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''Kidnap Party''\n|Alison Slater\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|''It's Not You, It's Me''\n|Sandy\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''Random Tropical Paradise''\n|Martha Crandall\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''Senior Moment''\n|Tess Woodson\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[I'll Be Next Door for Christmas]]''\n| Fran\n| Christmas comedy film written 